UPDATE [dbo].[MATURITY_QUESTIONS] SET [Question_Title]=N'3.F', [Sequence]=5, [Scope]=N'Organizational assets with remote access, such as workstations and human-machine interfaces (HMIs), where safe and technically feasible', [Recommend_Action]=N'<p>Organizations require MFA for access to assets using the strongest available method, if MFA is available for that asset.</p><p> MFA options sorted by strength, high to low, are as follows:</p><p>1. Phishing-resistant MFA (e.g., FIDO/WebAuthn or public key infrastructure (PKI)-based – see CISA guidance in “Resources”).</p><p>2. If Phishing-resistant MFA is not available, then mobile app-based soft tokens (preferably push notification with number matching).</p><p>3. MFA via short message service (SMS) or voice only used when no other options are possible.</p><p>IT: All IT accounts leverage MFA to access organizational resources. Prioritize accounts with highest risk, such as privileged administrative accounts for key IT systems.</p><p>OT: MFA is enabled on all accounts and systems that can be accessed remotely, including vendors/maintenance accounts, remotely accessible user and engineering workstations, and remotely accessible HMIs when available.   If MFA is not available, remove remote access, introduce additional segmentation steps and prioritize credential management.</p>', [Risk_Addressed]=N'Adversaries without prior knowledge of legitimate credentials might try commonly used passwords across various accounts to gain access. They might also systematically guess passwords using repetitive or iterative methods.', [Services]=N'<div><a href="https://www.cisa.gov/sites/default/files/publications/fact-sheet-implementing-phishing-resistant-mfa-508c.pdf" target="_blank">Implementing Phishing Resistant MFA</a></div><div><a href="https://www.cisa.gov/secure-our-world/turn-mfa" target="_blank">Protect Our World with MFA</a></div>', [Outcome]=N'Add a critical, additional layer of security to protect assets accounts. ', [Security_Practice]=N'Implement Multifactor Authentication (MFA)', [Implementation_Guides]=N'<p class="fst-italic">All bullets for an answer option must be satisfied to meet the criteria for that answer.</p>
<div class="sub-header-2">OT - Implemented</div>
<ul>
     <li>Within OT environments, MFA is enabled on all accounts and systems that can be accessed remotely, including
          vendors/maintenance accounts, remotely accessible user and engineering workstations, and remotely accessible
          human-machine interfaces (HMIs).</li>
     <li>When OT cannot support authentication, or the organization determines that it is not advisable due to adverse
          impacts on performance, safety, or reliability, does the organization employ compensating countermeasures such
          as the use of physical security to provide an equivalent security capability or level of protection for the
          OT?</li>
</ul>
<div class="sub-header-2">IT - Implemented</div>
<ul>
     <li>Does the organization implement MFA for access to assets using the strongest available method for that asset
          (see questions below for scope). MFA options sorted by strength, high to low, are as follows:
          <ol>
               <li>Hardware-based, phishing-resistant MFA (e.g., FIDO/WebAuthn or PKI based - see CISA guidance in
                    “Resources”);</li>
               <li>If such hardware-based MFA is not available, then mobile app-based soft tokens (preferably push
